I made this simple app to test shaders setUniform.
I'm working with cocos2d-js 3.9, the problem happens when compiling the native version of iOS.

The javascript code is the following:

``` javascript
var sp = new cc.Sprite(img);
shader = new cc.GLProgram();
shader.retain();
shader.init(res.colored_vsh, res.colored_fsh);
shader.addAttribute(cc.ATTRIBUTE_NAME_POSITION, cc.VERTEX_ATTRIB_POSITION);
shader.addAttribute(cc.ATTRIBUTE_NAME_COLOR, cc.VERTEX_ATTRIB_COLOR);
shader.addAttribute(cc.ATTRIBUTE_NAME_TEX_COORD, cc.VERTEX_ATTRIB_TEX_COORDS);
shader.link();
shader.updateUniforms();
sp.setShaderProgram(shader);
shader.use();
var color_mult_loc = shader.getUniformLocationForName('color_m');
shader.setUniformLocationWith1f(color_mult_loc, 1);
```

The problem is with the uniform `color_m` in the fragment shader, the code is:

```
precision lowp float;
varying vec4 v_fragmentColor; 
varying vec2 v_texCoord; 
uniform float color_m;

void main() 
{ 
    vec4 v_orColor = v_fragmentColor * texture2D(CC_Texture0, v_texCoord);

    gl_FragColor = vec4(v_orColor.r * color_m, v_orColor.g, v_orColor.b, v_orColor.a);
}
```

which in browser shows:

![screen shot 2015-12-28 at 11 05 00 am](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1079323/12090998/607bba98-b2d2-11e5-9a56-b1d591435120.png)

but in iOS shows:

![img_0037](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1079323/12091005/71e32050-b2d2-11e5-88cf-5e064581934a.PNG)

as you can see, in browser the value of the uniform `color_m` is `1`, which is fine because of the line `shader.setUniformLocationWith1f(color_mult_loc, 1);`, but in iOS is `0`. You can see in the second image how the red channel is mutiplied by `0`.

